# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ansible
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ansible/ansible-software] Originally written by Michael DeHaan in 2012, and acquired by Red Hat in 2015, Ansible is designed to configure both Unix-like systems and Microsoft Windows.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] Ansible is agentless, relying on temporary remote connections via SSH or Windows Remote Management which allows PowerShell execution.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] The Ansible control node runs on most Unix-like systems that are able to run Python, including Windows with Windows Subsystem for Linux installed.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] System configuration is defined in part by using its own declarative language.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] The term "ansible" was coined by Ursula K.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] Le Guin in her 1966 novel *Rocannon's World*, and refers to fictional instantaneous communication systems.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] The Ansible tool was developed by Michael DeHaan, the author of the provisioning server application Cobbler and co-author of the Fedora Unified Network Controller (Func) framework for remote administration.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] (originally AnsibleWorks, Inc.) was the company founded in 2013 by DeHaan, Timothy Gerla, and Saïd Ziouani to commercially support and sponsor Ansible.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] Red Hat acquired Ansible in October 2015.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] Ansible helps to manage multiple machines by selecting portions of Ansible's inventory stored in simple plain text files.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] The inventory is configurable, and target machine inventory can be sourced dynamically or from cloud-based sources in different formats (YAML, INI).
[src:ansible/ansible-software] Sensitive data can be stored in encrypted files using Ansible Vault since 2014.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] In contrast with other popular configuration-management software — such as Chef, Puppet, Salt and CFEngine — Ansible uses an *agentless* architecture, with Ansible software not normally running or even installed on the controlled node.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] Instead, Ansible orchestrates a node by installing and running *modules* on the node temporarily via SSH.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] For the duration of an orchestration task, a process running the module communicates with the controlling machine with a JSON-based protocol via its standard input and output.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] When Ansible is not managing a node, it does not consume resources on the node because no daemons are run or software installed.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] Ansible requires Python to be installed on all managing machines, including pip package manager along with configuration-management software and its dependent packages.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] Managed network devices require no extra dependencies and are agentless.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] The control node (master host) is intended to manage (orchestrate) target machines (nodes termed as "inventory", see below).
[src:ansible/ansible-software] Control nodes can be run from Linux and Unix-like operating systems (including MacOS); Windows OSs are only supported through the Windows Subsystem for Linux.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] Ansible does not require a single controlling machine for orchestration, ensuring that disaster recovery is simple.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] Nodes are managed by the controlling node over SSH.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] Modules are mostly standalone and can be written in a standard scripting language (such as Python, Perl, Ruby, Bash, etc.).
[src:ansible/ansible-software] One of the guiding goals of modules is idempotency, which means that even if an operation is repeated multiple times (e.g., upon recovery from an outage), it will always place the system into the same state.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] Location of target nodes is specified through inventory configuration lists (INI or YAML formatted) located at `/etc/ansible/hosts` (on Linux).
[src:ansible/ansible-software] The configuration file lists either the IP address or hostname of each node that is accessible by Ansible.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] In addition, nodes can be assigned to groups.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] This configuration file specifies three nodes: the first node is specified by an IP address, and the latter two nodes are specified by hostnames.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] Additionally, the latter two nodes are grouped under the `webservers` group.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] Ansible can also use a custom *Dynamic Inventory* script, which can dynamically pull data from a different system, and supports groups of groups.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] Playbooks are YAML files that store lists of tasks for repeated executions on managed nodes.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] Each Playbook maps (associates) a group of hosts to a set of roles.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] Each role is represented by calls to Ansible tasks.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] The Ansible Automation Platform (AAP) is a REST API, web service, and web-based interface (application) designed to make Ansible more accessible to people with a wide range of IT skillsets.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] It is a platform composed of multiple components including developer tooling, an operations interface, as well as an Automation Mesh to enable automation tasks at scale across data centers.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] AAP is a commercial product supported by Red Hat, Inc. but derived from 17+ upstream open source projects including the AWX upstream project (formerly Ansible Tower), which has been open source since September 2017.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] There also is another open source alternative to Tower, Semaphore, written in Go.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] Control machines have to be a Linux/Unix host (for example BSD, CentOS, Debian, macOS, Red Hat Enterprise Linux, SUSE Linux Enterprise, Ubuntu), and Python 2.7 or 3.5 is required.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] Managed nodes, if they are Unix-like, must have Python 2.4 or later.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] For managed nodes with Python 2.5 or earlier, the `python-simplejson` package is also required.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] Since version 1.7, Ansible can also manage Windows nodes.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] In this case, native PowerShell remoting supported by the WS-Management protocol is used instead of SSH.
[src:ansible/ansible-software] Ansible can deploy to bare metal hosts, virtual machines, and cloud environments.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] CM applied over the lifecycle of a system provides visibility and control of its performance, functional, and physical attributes.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] CM verifies that a system performs as intended, and is documented in sufficient detail to support its projected life cycle.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] The CM process facilitates orderly management of system information and system changes for purposes such as to revise capability; improve performance, reliability, or maintainability; extend life; reduce costs; reduce risk and liability; or correct defects.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] The relatively minimal cost of implementing CM is returned manyfold in cost avoidance.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] The lack of CM (or its ineffectual implementation) can be very expensive and sometimes can have such catastrophic consequences such as failure of equipment or loss of life.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] CM emphasizes the functional relation between parts, subsystems, and systems for effectively controlling system change.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] It helps to verify that proposed changes are systematically considered to minimize adverse effects.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] Changes to the system are proposed, evaluated, and implemented using a standardized, systematic approach that ensures consistency, and proposed changes are evaluated in terms of their anticipated impact on the entire system.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] CM verifies that changes are carried out as specified and that documentation of items and systems reflects their true configuration.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] A complete CM program includes provisions for the storing, tracking, and updating of all system information on a component, subsystem, and system basis.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] A structured CM program ensures that documentation (e.g., requirements, design, test, and acceptance documentation) for items is accurate and consistent with the actual physical design of the item.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] In many cases, without CM, the documentation exists but is not consistent with the item itself.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] For this reason, engineers, contractors, and management are frequently forced to develop documentation reflecting the actual status of the item before they can proceed with a change.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] This reverse engineering process is wasteful in terms of human and other resources and can be minimized or eliminated using CM.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] Configuration management originated in the United States Department of Defense in the 1950s as a technical management discipline for hardware material items—and it is now a standard practice in virtually every industry.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] The CM process became its own technical discipline in the late 1960s when the DoD developed a series of military standards called the "480 series" (i.e., MIL-STD-480, MIL-STD-481 and MIL-STD-483) that were subsequently issued in the 1970s.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] This marked the beginning of what has now evolved into the most widely distributed and accepted standard on CM, ANSI–EIA–649–1998.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] Many of these functions and models have redefined CM from its traditional holistic approach to technical management.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] Some treat CM as being similar to a librarian activity and break out change control or change management as a separate or standalone discipline.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] CM is the practice of handling changes systematically so that a system maintains its integrity over time.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] CM implements the policies, procedures, techniques, and tools that manage, evaluate proposed changes, track change status, and maintain an inventory of system and support documents as the system changes.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] CM programs and plans provide technical and administrative direction to the development and implementation of the procedures, functions, services, tools, processes, and resources required to successfully develop and support a complex system.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] During system development, CM allows program management to track requirements throughout the life-cycle through acceptance and operations and maintenance.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] As changes inevitably occur in the requirements and design, they must be approved and documented, creating an accurate record of the system status.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] Ideally the CM process is applied throughout the system life cycle.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] Many professionals mix up or get confused with Asset management (AM, see also ISO/IEC 19770), where it inventories the assets on hand.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] The key difference between CM and AM is that the former does not manage the financial accounting aspect but the service that the system supports or in other words, that the latter (AM) is trying to realize value from an IT asset.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] The CM process for both hardware and software configuration items comprises five distinct disciplines as established in the MIL–HDBK–61A and in ANSI/EIA-649.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] Members of an organization interested in applying a standard change-management process will employ these disciplines as policies and procedures for establishing baselines, manage and control change, and monitor and assess the effectiveness and correctness of progress.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] The IEEE 12207 process IEEE 12207.2 also has these activities and adds "Release management and delivery".
[src:ansible/configuration-management] Configuration Identification (CI): consists of setting and maintaining baselines, which define the system or subsystem architecture, components, and any developments at any point in time.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] It is the basis by which changes to any part of a system are identified, documented, and later tracked through design, development, testing, and final delivery.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] CI incrementally establishes and maintains the definitive current basis for Configuration Status Accounting (CSA) of a system and its configuration items (CIs) throughout their life cycle (development, production, deployment, and operational support) until disposal.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] Configuration Control: includes the evaluation of all change-requests and change-proposals, and their subsequent approval or disapproval.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] It covers the process of controlling modifications to the system's design, hardware, firmware, software, and documentation.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] Configuration Status Accounting: includes the process of recording and reporting configuration item descriptions (e.g., hardware, software, firmware, etc.) and all departures from the baseline during design and production.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] In the event of suspected problems, operators can quickly verify baseline configuration and approved modifications.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] Configuration Verification and Audit: an independent review of hardware and software for the purpose of assessing compliance with established performance requirements, commercial and appropriate military standards, and functional, allocated, and product baselines.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] Configuration audits verify that the system and subsystem configuration documentation complies with the functional and physical performance characteristics before acceptance into an architectural baseline.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] The software configuration management (SCM) process is looked upon by practitioners as the best solution to handling changes in software projects.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] It identifies the functional and physical attributes of software at various points in time, and performs systematic control of changes to the identified attributes for the purpose of maintaining software integrity and traceability throughout the software development life cycle.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] The SCM process further defines the need to trace changes, and the ability to verify that the final delivered software has all of the planned enhancements that are supposed to be included in the release.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] It identifies four procedures that must be defined for each software project to ensure that a sound SCM process is implemented.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] These terms and definitions can change somewhat from standard to standard.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] ITIL specifies the use of a configuration management system (CMS) or configuration management database (CMDB) as a means of achieving industry best practices for Configuration Management.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] CMS helps manage a federated collection of CMDBs.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] The benefits of a CMS/CMDB includes being able to perform functions like root cause analysis, impact analysis, change management, and current state assessment for future state strategy development.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] For information assurance, CM can be defined as the management of security features and assurances through control of changes made to hardware, software, firmware, documentation, test, test fixtures, and test documentation throughout the life cycle of an information system.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] For example, configuration requirements may be different for a network firewall that functions as part of an organization's Internet boundary versus one that functions as an internal local network firewall.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] Configuration management is used to maintain an understanding of the status of complex assets with a view to maintaining the highest level of serviceability for the lowest cost.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] Specifically, it aims to ensure that operations are not disrupted due to the asset (or parts of the asset) overrunning limits of planned lifespan or below quality levels.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] In the military, this type of activity is often classed as "mission readiness", and seeks to define which assets are available and for which type of mission; a classic example is whether aircraft on board an aircraft carrier are equipped with bombs for ground support or missiles for defense.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] Configuration management can be used to maintain OS configuration files.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] Many of these systems utilize Infrastructure as Code to define and maintain configuration.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] The Promise theory of configuration maintenance was developed by Mark Burgess, with a practical implementation on present day computer systems in the software CFEngine able to perform real time repair as well as preventive maintenance.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] Understanding the "as is" state of an asset and its major components is an essential element in preventive maintenance as used in maintenance, repair, and overhaul and enterprise asset management systems.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] Complex assets such as aircraft, ships, industrial machinery etc. depend on many different components being serviceable.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] This serviceability is often defined in terms of the amount of usage the component has had since it was new, since fitted, since repaired, the amount of use it has had over its life and several other limiting factors.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] Understanding how near the end of their life each of these components is has been a major undertaking involving labor-intensive record keeping until recent developments in software.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] Many types of component use electronic sensors to capture data which provides live condition monitoring.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] This data is analyzed on board or at a remote location by computer to evaluate its current serviceability and increasingly its likely future state using algorithms which predict potential future failures based on previous examples of failure through field experience and modeling.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] This is the basis for "predictive maintenance".
[src:ansible/configuration-management] Availability of accurate and timely data is essential in order for CM to provide operational value and a lack of this can often be a limiting factor.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] Capturing and disseminating the operating data to the various support organizations is becoming an industry in itself.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] The consumers of this data have grown more numerous and complex with the growth of programs offered by original equipment manufacturers (OEMs).
[src:ansible/configuration-management] These are designed to offer operators guaranteed availability and make the picture more complex with the operator managing the asset but the OEM taking on the liability to ensure its serviceability.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] More recently configuration management has been applied to large construction projects which can often be very complex and have a huge number of details and changes that need to be documented.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] Construction agencies such as the Federal Highway Administration have used configuration management for their infrastructure projects.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] There are construction-based configuration management tools that aim to document change orders and RFIs in order to ensure a project stays on schedule and on budget.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] These programs can also store information to aid in the maintenance and modification of the infrastructure when it is completed.
[src:ansible/configuration-management] This study yielded results indicating a benefit to using configuration management on projects of this nature.
